Free Trade Fanatics
From Cambridge — — I recently accepted an invitation to guest lecture in two colleagues' globalization course at Harvard. “I have to warn you,”
one of them reminded me beforehand, “these students are all ardent supporters of globalization.”
He had them make a choice between free trade and import restrictions in the very first class, and over 90% chose the former.
Before even starting to teach the magical effect of comparative advantage.
We know that in real surveys, using the same questions to ask representative samples - - not Harvard students - - would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of those who oppose trade restrictions to those who support them is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students would not be particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education tend to be more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their own future prospects (money) and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different way, emphasizing the distribution effects that trade may bring.
As a result, the consensus on fair trade completely disappeared, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone if they agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, and then told them that I could make $200 in Nicholas' account disappear — — vanish! — — while simultaneously making John's account increase by $300, and the social engineering feat could make the entire class gain an extra $100 in value.
So would they agree to participate in this little trick?
Only a very small part of them agreed decisively, while many people hesitated, and even more people opposed implementing this change.

It's clear that the students couldn't tolerate this large-scale income redistribution, even if the entire economic cake was made bigger.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, while free trade would also lead to a similar - - in fact, even more drastic - - wealth redistribution from losers to winners.
Students looked stunned.
I went on to say, let's assume Nicholas and John both opened up a small competitive company.
John worked harder, saved more, invested more, and produced a better product, so not only did he have $300 more than Nicholas, but also drove Nicholas' company out of the market and caused a loss of $200 to Nicholas.
How many students agreed to this change?
This time, most of them voted in favor - - in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothetical scenario directly related to international trade.
What if John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or if he outsourced his business to China where labor rights are not fully developed?
Or if he hired child labor in Indonesia?
The level of agreement with this change then decreased accordingly with each option.
Besides, technological innovation will also cause some people to be in a weaker position, just like trade. What's your attitude towards this?
Only a few students are willing to restrict the development of technology.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs in order to protect the jobs of candle makers is a ridiculous idea.
Therefore, they are not necessarily opposed to redistribution, but rather to certain specific forms of redistribution.
Just like most of us, they are concerned with the justice of the process.
If we want to make a judgment about the result of redistribution, we must know the objective environment that produces this result.
We wouldn't be upset about Bill Gates' or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their competitors have been living a hard life, probably because they and their competitors are all operating according to the same basic rules and facing extremely similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett became rich through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or government subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be completely different.
If we cannot tolerate the redistribution achieved by breaking domestic moral rules, why can we be so calm about it when it involves international trade?
Similarly, when we expect the redistribution effect to be equalized in the long run, and everyone will eventually benefit from it, we are likely to ignore the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that, even though technology may bring negative responses to some people in the short term, we still want to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continues to impact the same group of people - - low-skilled blue-collar workers - - we are worried about globalization.
However, many economists have ignored these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute our worries about globalization to the stupid and selfish motivations of trade protectionism or ignorance, not knowing that the most important thing is actually a moral issue.
Lacking the awareness that international trade may sometimes - - not always - - lead to some redistribution consequences that we cannot accept in our domestic society, these economists are also unable to intervene in public discussions appropriately.
But since they can't stand on moral grounds, how can they defend trade so strongly?
When globalization occasionally triggers a complicated issue related to the legitimacy of redistribution, we shouldn't instinctively respond with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to be weighed, including the fact that globalization may inflict more severe wealth deprivation on people in other places than the victims in the United States.
Democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion and make more conscious and more deliberate decisions on this matter.
Engaging in such infatuation with globalization simply because it has expanded the economic cake will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization in the long run.
